ef=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousecontractsbountiesjobsquestsetc.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2646.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Brad's new company</span><hr size=1> They have the luxury of being able to avoid all the early mistakes made by the various online games out there.  If I were a betting man, I would be inclined to think they will develop a game better then anything currently out right now.  A game with the bredth and depth of EQ in content (perhaps even greater) and using some of the latest technology in graphics to create a visually stunning world.  Their experience should hopefully give them a leg up in development time, but I doubt we will see any product from them until a few years out.<br>
<br>
New generation games are going to require lots of content if they are going to compete with the games out there now.  My biggest beef with DaoC was the lack of content and diversity.  It was visually good (and didn't suffer from large amounts of play-breaking bugs,) but you could tell after playing for a few weeks that they needed to spend a lot more time on content.<br>
<br>
In a couple years, I should be ready to quit EQ and get my hands on something new.  I'm addicted to the genre now.<br>
<br>
Also, I have no doubt their company will partner with a big distributer of some sort once they get further along in their project.  It's just the way the business works.<br>
